# js/JsMaterialXGenShader.data is an Emscripten-packed virtual filesystem
# archive: concatenated .mtlx text files with ZERO NUL bytes anywhere in the
# 1.4MB payload. Git's automatic text/binary detection keys off NUL-byte
# presence, so it misclassifies this file as text. On a Windows clone with
# core.autocrlf=true, git therefore CRLF-converts every LF in the archive at
# checkout. Each inserted CR shifts the packed virtual-filesystem's internal
# byte offsets, corrupting the archive and breaking the MaterialX standard
# library load at runtime (e.g. "XML parse error in
# /libraries/bxdf/disney_principled.mtlx at character 7307", diagnosed on a
# fresh clone). The .wasm files survive this heuristic only because they
# happen to contain NUL bytes.
#
# Fix: force explicit binary handling for known binary asset types so git
# never applies EOL conversion to them, regardless of content heuristics or
# local autocrlf settings.
#
# Note: .mtlx is intentionally NOT marked binary here. Those files are read
# as standalone text documents (not packed archives), where CRLF conversion
# is harmless.

*.data binary
*.wasm binary
*.glb binary
*.hdr binary
*.exr binary
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.tif binary
*.tiff binary
*.gif binary
*.ico binary
*.woff binary
*.woff2 binary

# vendor/ holds third-party assets collected by `npm run vendor` (see
# scripts/vendor.mjs). Mark it vendored for GitHub linguist stats, and force
# git to skip all EOL/text conversion for every file under it regardless of
# extension-based text/binary heuristics — the same class of heuristic
# mis-detection documented above corrupted JsMaterialXGenShader.data on a
# fresh Windows clone, and vendored .js/.css/font files must not risk it.
vendor/** linguist-vendored
vendor/** -text

# js/gen/ holds build-generated artifacts (see
# scripts/extract-mtlx-version.mjs) that are byte-compared by --check; force
# LF so a Windows checkout's autocrlf setting can never make that comparison
# (or a plain git diff) spuriously fail.
js/gen/** text eol=lf
